observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE):
Require the City Accountant to provide GSO the data and all supporting documents of the identified reconciling items for proper recording in the RPCPPE. Also, together with GSO, verify/reconcile the difference noted amounting to P1,163,842.97 and make the necessary adjustments accordingly;
Instruct the GSO to -
record the identified reconciling items in the RPCPPE upon receipt of the supporting documents from CAO to come up with the reconciled balances between the accounting and property records;
monitor properly and regularly the inventory of land titles and ensure safekeeping of the same; and
henceforth, secure the owner’s duplicate copy of the TCTs/OCTs and other pertinent documents required for the transfer of the land titles under the name of the City;
Direct the CBO, City Treasurer, and GSO to provide sufficient funding for the transfer of the land titles under the name of the City so that the interest of the City against third party claims, if any, is fully protected; and
Henceforth, strictly comply with the provisions of the aforementioned laws, rules and regulations.

We recommended that the LCE direct:
The City Property Inventory Committee to -
reconcile, together with GSO and CAO, the variance noted amounting to P1,727,006,269.94 and make the necessary adjustments accordingly;
prepare and submit the RPCPPE, and reconcile the result thereof with the property and accounting records;
remove from the RCPPE the PPE items totaling P15,428,640.00 already disposed of.
The GSO to -
initiate the disposal procedures for unserviceable PPE items in compliance with the abovementioned law, rules and regulations and coordinate with CAO for the proper derecognition in the books;
demand from accountable officers/employees the missing PPE items and require them to submit Request for Relief from Accountability pursuant to the existing laws, rules and regulations; and
Henceforth, the CAO, GSO and CPIC to strictly comply with the provisions of the aforementioned laws, rules and regulations. Also, consider adopting the COA Circular 2020-006 dated                   January 31, 2020, prescribing the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances.

We recommended that the LCE:
Direct the GSO and CEO to coordinate and come up with the complete and proper identification of all City-owned insurable properties for purposes of insurance coverage with the GSIS-GIF;
Require the GSO/Inventory Committee to prepare the PIF for all insurable properties of the City and submit the same to COA and GSIS- GIF not later than April 30 of each year, pursuant to COA Circular No. 2018-002;
Direct the CBO to provide adequate funding for the payment of insurance premiums covering all insurable properties of the City;
Direct the GSO and the City Legal Officer to expedite the processing of the transfer of ownership of all donated properties so that insurance coverage thereof shall be shouldered by the recipient Barangays; and
Henceforth, strictly comply with the provisions of RA No. 656, as amended by PD No. 245, requiring the insurance of government property with the GSIS-GIF.

We recommended that the LCE direct:
The CAO and the CTO to –
coordinate and reconcile treasury cash books and SLs; review and analyze the discrepancies noted and make the necessary adjustments in both records. Thereafter, perform periodic reconciliation between the SL and cashbooks;
exert efforts to retrieve the records/supporting documents of all dormant bank accounts for possible return to the SAs and/or recognize the same as income;
consider closing all dormant bank accounts, as well as the overdraft accounts, and transfer the balances to the City’s General Fund active bank accounts;
The CAO to –
exhaust all possible means to locate the documents relative to prior years’ reconciling items, including requesting a copy of the transaction history from the depository bank, for proper adjustment in the books; and
record the amount of P5,207,23.03 for the bank balance under the City’s account in UBP as of December 31, 2021, and verify the unrecorded PNB bank account with overdraft balance of P665,093.41; thereafter, prepare the monthly BRS for each depository account with UBP and submit regularly the BRS to this Office pursuant to Section 3.2 of COA Circular No. 96-011.

We recommended that the LCE:
Require all accountable officers with outstanding CAs to immediately submit liquidation documents to the CAO and return/refund all unutilized CAs to the CTO;
Direct the City Accountant to:
issue demand letters to those AOs who are in active service for the immediate settlement of their CAs, otherwise, cause the withholding of their salaries;
prepare aging of dormant unliquidated cash advances on a quarterly basis to support the request for write-off of the accounts which remained outstanding from CY 2011 and prior years and whose AOs were already deceased and with unknown whereabouts;
Direct the City Legal Officer to:
initiate legal measures/remedies to recover those unliquidated CAs of retired personnel and those that are dormant and long outstanding; and
submit status of the pending administrative case filed against AO No. 9 for proper disclosure in the books.

We recommended that the LCE direct:
The LFC and other concerned Departments to –
ensure that in planning for the infrastructure projects, the appropriate timing and phasing of the implementation of the identified priority PPAs, such as; the detailed engineering investigations, surveys and designs of the project in totality, and availability of the right-of-way site or location, should be considered prior to inclusion in the City’s AIP;
conduct a thorough planning and exercise prudence in the allocation of funds of development projects to be funded under the 20% DF to avoid incurrence of multiple funding of PPAs;
The City Treasurer, CAO and CBO analyze and determine actual amount of DF to be transferred to the CDF bank account and ensure that all projects charged to the fund should be sufficiently backed-up by cash to avoid incurrence of overdraft; and
Henceforth, all concerned Officials monitor and evaluate the status of implementation as well as the utilization of the 20% DF and ensure timely implementation/completion of the City’s development projects pursuant to DILG DBM JMC No. 2017-01.

We recommended that the LCE:
Institutionalize a GAD monitoring and evaluation (M&E) system for the effective and efficient implementation of GAD PPAs in order to fully maximize the potential benefits that the intended beneficiaries can derive therefrom;
Instruct the GAD M&E team, together with the implementing Departments/Offices, to ensure that GAD PPAs are implemented as planned to attain the GAD objectives and to monitor and implement only programs and projects that are contained in the reviewed and evaluated annual GPB or as appropriately revised;
Develop the GAD database with adequate and systematically gathered sex-disaggregated data and other gender-related information which will provide the bases for gender analysis, planning, programming and policy formulation; and
Henceforth, strictly adhere to the pertinent provisions of Sections 4.1.B, 4.C.3.3 and 4.C.7.2 of the PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01 and Section 37 of the MCW-IRR.

We recommended that the LCE:
Direct the City Treasurer to immediately revert the unutilized fund of P13,951,000.00 to the BTr except those with pending appeal with the Grievance Committee as prescribed by LBC Nos. 136, 137 and 138;
Instruct and/or require the LFC and the City Accountant to reconcile their records to account for the difference of P343,000.00;
Require the City Treasurer to submit the list of beneficiaries with pending appeals to the Grievance Committee totaling P8,746,000.00;
Require the Accountable Officers to immediately submit the liquidation report to the Accounting Office for the cash advance amounting to P169,000.00 for proper recording in the books; and
Henceforth, for similar financial assistance, direct the disbursing officer and the barangay officials concerned to ensure submission of necessary documentary requirements in order to efficiently facilitate the proper and immediate liquidation of the cash advances in compliance to laws, rules and regulations.

We recommended that the LCE require the CAO and HRMO to:
Analyze and reconcile their respective records pertaining to the unremitted prior year transactions, current year’s unreconciled differences and other adjustments, and make the necessary corrections/adjustments in their respective records/reports;
Remit all the contributions, premium payments, loan amortizations and other amounts withheld from employees, including government share, to the concerned agencies to avoid incurrence of penalties and surcharges and enable the members/beneficiaries to receive/avail the benefits due them from said agencies;
Strengthen internal accounting and administrative controls on monitoring and review of withheld amounts payable to GSIS,             Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth, including government share/contributions; and
Henceforth, strictly comply with the above-mentioned laws, rules and regulations.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE): |  |  |  | 
 |  |  |  |  | 
 | Require the CAO and GSO to –

Reconcile the accounting records with the RPCPPE-Land, and investigate and clear discrepancies, if any;




Prepare and maintain PPE Ledger Cards and Property Stock Cards, respectively, for proper control and monitoring of the Land account;

Direct the City Budget Officer, City Treasurer, and GSO to –

Provide funding for the transfer of titles of 113 parcels of land in the name of the City;



Prioritize registration and transfer of titles of the parcels of land to prove absolute ownership and ensure protection of the interest of the City;

Direct the GSO, CAO, and other concerned offices to – 

Locate documents/ records to substantiate ownership over      49 parcels of land without TCTs;


Facilitate the issuance of titles in the name of the City;

Create and direct the appraisal committee to determine cost or fair valuation of 18 parcels of land without recorded acquisition costs for proper recording/recognition in the books;

Direct the GSO, in coordination with the LHDO, to – 

Release the titles of fully paid lots to socialized housing beneficiaries;


Provide information thereof to CAO for proper recording in the books;


Direct the GSO to – 

Ensure that all parcels of land owned by the City are included in the RPCPPE;

Properly monitor the inventory of land titles and ensure safekeeping of the same; and

Secure the owner’s duplicate copy of the TCTs/Original Certificates of Title and other pertinent documents required for the transfer of the land titles under the name of the City.

We recommended that: |  |  |  | 
 |  |  |  |  | 
 | GSO and CAO conduct reconciliation of the PPE accounts to determine the cause/s of unreconciled difference between accounting records and RPCPPE, and effect appropriate adjustments;

GSO and CEO corroborate to verify PPEs not included in the RPCPPE, and reconcile the same with the records of CAO;

The LCE –

Create an inventory committee with adequate number of members and representatives from the GSO, CAO, and concerned offices in accordance with COA Circular                 No. 2020-006;

Prioritize the completion of the physical inventory count of PPEs;

Prepare the RPCPPE, reconcile the same with the GSO and CAO records, and CAO to prepare the necessary adjusting entries for one-time cleansing of PPE for reconciling items;


The CAO prepare a comprehensive lapsing schedule with specific identification for each PPE classification that will ensure appropriate, complete and accurate basis and computation of depreciation;

The GSO initiate the disposal procedures for unserviceable motor vehicles in compliance with Section 379, Title VI, Book II, RA No. 7160 in relation to COA Circular No. 92-386, and coordinate with CAO for the proper dropping of said vehicles in the books; and

The CEO, GSO, and CAO exert all possible efforts to locate the relevant documents related to the demolished Legislative Building for derecognition in the books.

The CTO and CAO to – 

Coordinate and reconcile treasury cash books and subsidiary ledgers (SLs); 



Review and analyze the discrepancies;



The CAO to effect necessary adjustments in the books to establish the correct balances in both records. Thereafter, perform periodic reconciliation between the SL and cashbooks;

The CAO to – 

Prepare adjusting entries for the CY 2020 reconciling items;

The LCE –

Ensure strict compliance with the provisions of COA         Circular No. 97-002 and Section 89 of PD No. 1445 on the grant, utilization and liquidation of CAs;

Require all concerned AOs and employees to settle their outstanding CAs immediately by demanding the submission of the liquidation reports and its supporting documents. Otherwise, cause the withholding or suspension of their salaries for non-compliance therewith;

Direct the City Legal Officer to institute immediate appropriate action and/or legal remedies for AOs who vehemently refused to liquidate their outstanding CAs and to recommend appropriate actions for AOs already separated and/or deceased;

The City Accountant, in coordination with the City Treasurer –

Stop the practice of granting additional CAs to AOs unless the previous one has been liquidated or a proper accounting thereof has been made; and

Monitor submission of liquidation documents and render full accounting of the balances of the CAs and ensure timely reporting thereof after the purpose for which it was given has been served.

The Inventory Committee/GSO –

Conduct periodic physical count of all supplies and materials, prepare the RPCI and submit the same to the CAO for proper reconciliation of the inventory accounts;



Prepare and submit to the CAO the consolidated report of SSMIs based on RIS, on a monthly basis, for proper recording of the expenses in the books;

The City Accountant –

Recognize all supplies and materials purchased during the year as inventory and record the related expense account upon issuance or distribution pursuant to IPSAS 12; and

Refrain from restating the inventory beginning balances issued in the current year.

The City Accountant –

Review and analyze the recorded payables which remained outstanding for over two years, and if warranted, be reverted to the GF as prescribed in Section 98 of PD No. 1445;

Record obligations for infrastructure projects based on progress billings and/or statement of work accomplished submitted by the contractor duly certified by the City Engineer and ensure that the amount obligated is the actual cost incurred as at year end;

Evaluate the outstanding payable for supply and delivery of CCTV and network infrastructure, and make the necessary adjustments in the books;

Prepare the necessary adjusting journal entries to correct the net overstatement of the recorded payables of P255.192 million, thereafter, make appropriate adjustments on accounts/items similarly situated; 

Effect the necessary adjustments to correct the misclassified accounts. Subsequently, record obligations based on the actual nature of the transaction and in compliance with IPSAS;

The City Engineer –

Require the contractor for the submission of progress billings and/or statement of work accomplished as at year end and forward the same to the CAO for proper recording of payables/obligations in the books; and 

Submit actual status of the project on supply, design, installation, testing and commissioning of CCTV and Network Infrastructure for proper accounting thereof.

The City Accountant to - 
Review and analyze the Journal Entry Voucher for the collections/ remittances pertaining to PhilHealth claims for hospital bills, and make the necessary adjusting journal entries to record the same as Hospital Fees in the GF books pursuant to Section 21 of RA No. 11223 and Sections 105 and 109 of the MNGAS for LGUs;

Adopt the accrual method of accounting in the recording of hospital claims by recording receivables from PhilHealth in accordance with Section 7 of IPSAS;

Hereafter, maintain subsidiary records for PhilHealth receivables, and regularly conduct monitoring and reconciliation of the account with the OsPar records;
The OsPar Accounting Officer to - 

Prepare and submit the summary of the remittances from PhilHealth claims pertaining to hospital bills for proper recording of income in the GF books;

Prepare and submit the schedule of claims upon transmittal to PhilHealth to CAO for proper recording of the receivables; and

Conduct regular reconciliation with PhilHealth for the outstanding claims.

We recommended that the LCE:

Stop the grant of transportation allowance to officials with issued and/or using government vehicles pursuant to the abovementioned rules and regulations, otherwise, this will be disallowed in audit;

Submit justification on the 11 service vehicles assigned to and used by unentitled employees pursuant to DBM Budget Circular (BC)    No. 2017-1 and DBM LBC No. 103;

Direct the GSO to regularly update the list of officials and employees with assigned service vehicles and furnish the HRMO a copy of the list to ensure that officials and employees with  assigned service vehicles and allowed to reimburse gasoline expenses are excluded from the TA payroll; and

Require the concerned City officials who are receiving TA to submit a certification that they are not using or issued with government vehicles.

We recommended that the LCE require the:

City Planning Officer and the City Budget Officer to utilize the     20% DF pursuant to DILG – DBM JMC No. 2017-01 and ensure that the implementation of all identified PPAs be given priority in order to attain the full realization of the program and help achieve desirable socio-economic development and environmental outcomes of the City;

City Planning Officer, in coordination with the City Engineer, to monitor regularly the rate of progress of each project, assure the completion of prior years’ unimplemented PPAs, as necessary;

The City Budget Officer, in coordination with the City Planning Officer, to ensure that the proposed PPAs chargeable against the Fund are detailed and itemized for proper budgeting, planning, and utilization/implementation; and

The City Budget Officer and the City Treasurer, to determine actual amount of DF to be transferred to the CDF bank account to avoid incurrence of overdraft and ensure that all projects charged to the fund should be sufficiently backed-up by cash.

We recommended that the LCE direct the:

The CAO, the CTO, together with the HRMO, to strictly adhere to the provisions of RR No. 02-98, as amended by RR No. 14-2002, for the efficient and timely remittance of taxes withheld to the BIR to avoid penalties and surcharges for late remittances;

The CAO to review and analyze the details of the SL balances of Due to BIR account, particularly those with excess remittances, in order to arrive at the correct amount of taxes due for immediate remittance to the BIR, and to prepare the necessary adjustments to reflect the correct balance for fair presentation of the account in the financial statements;

The HRMO to ensure prompt and timely submission of the supporting documents for withholding and remittance of taxes on employees for proper recording in the books; and

Henceforth, the CAO to conduct regular review and monitoring of the Due to BIR account.

We recommended that Management:

Strictly adhere to Item V of COA Circular No. 2014-001 dated March 18, 2014 for the timely submission of the said reports to the COA Audit Team;

Maximize the utilization of GAD- related programs and projects to attain the objectives for which the funds were provided;

Require the GAD Focal Point System to  
(i) Establish a GAD Database with sufficient and systematically gathered sex disaggregated data that will provide the bases for gender analysis; (ii) Undertake gender analysis to identify and confirm existing gender issues; and (iii) revisit Annex B of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-01 which identifies the data requirements for particular gender issues.
